    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Here is a summary of the key contents of the January 6, 2025, 8-K filing by U.S. Steel regarding the Nippon Steel merger litigation:\n\n**Core Event: Two Lawsuits Filed**\n\nOn January 6, 2025, U.S. Steel and Nippon Steel Corporation (NSC) jointly filed two lawsuits in response to President Biden\'s January 3, 2025, executive order blocking their proposed $14.9 billion merger.\n\n**Lawsuit 1: Against the U.S. Government (Filed in D.C. Circuit Court)**\n\n- **Defendants:** The President of the United States and the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States (CFIUS).\n- **Key Allegations:**\n    - The President and CFIUS violated the companies\' constitutional due process and statutory rights.\n    - CFIUS failed to properly review the merger on national security grounds.\n    - The President\'s order blocking the deal was based on "purely political reasons" that are irrelevant and detrimental to U.S. national security.\n\n**Lawsuit 2: Against Competitors and Union (Filed in Western District of Pennsylvania)**\n\n- **Defendants:** Cleveland-Cliffs Inc., its CEO Lourenco Goncalves, and United Steelworkers (USW) International President David McCall.\n- **Key Allegations:**\n    - These parties engaged in a coordinated series of "anticompetitive and racketeering activities."\n    - Their goal was to illegally prevent any party other than Cleveland-Cliffs from acquiring U.S. Steel.\n    - The alleged actions were part of an "illegal campaign to monopolize critical domestic steel markets."\n\n**Other Key Details in the Filing:**\n\n- **Purpose of Filing:** The information was disclosed under "Regulation FD" (Fair Disclosure) and is considered "furnished," not "filed," to limit liability under securities laws.\n- **Press Release:** A joint press release detailing the lawsuits is attached as Exhibit 99.1.\n- **Forward-Looking Statements:** The filing includes a cautionary note about forward-looking statements, highlighting risks and uncertainties related to the proposed transaction and litigation.',
