        output='Here is a summary of the key contents of the press release from U.S. Steel and Nippon Steel dated January 3, 2025:\n\n**Core Message: Condemnation of the Block**\nThe press release strongly condemns President Biden\'s decision to block the proposed acquisition of U.S. Steel by Nippon Steel. The companies call the decision **"unlawful"** and a **"clear violation of due process"** , arguing it was manipulated to advance President Biden\'s political agenda rather than based on credible evidence of a national security risk.\n\n**Key Arguments:**\n- **No National Security Threat:** The companies assert that the government\'s order presents no credible evidence of a national security issue, making it a purely political decision.\n- **Corrupted Process:** They claim the CFIUS (Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States) review process was "deeply corrupted by politics" with a predetermined outcome. They note that CFIUS provided no written feedback on the four robust national security agreements they proactively offered over 100 days.\n- **Damage to U.S. Interests:** The companies argue the block harms American steelworkers, denies billions in committed investment (including $1 billion for Mon Valley Works and $300 million for Gary Works), puts thousands of union jobs at risk, and sends a "chilling message" to allied countries like Japan about investing in the U.S.\n\n**Proposed Mitigation Measures Offered:**\nThe companies highlight the voluntary, enforceable commitments they made to address any concerns, including:\n- Majority U.S. citizens on the board of directors.\n- A U.S. citizen CEO and CFO.\n- A prohibition on transferring any production or jobs outside the U.S.\n- A 10-year guarantee (subject to CFIUS approval) not to reduce production capacity at key U.S. facilities.\n- Regular reporting to CFIUS and allowing a U.S. government observer on the board.\n\n**Next Steps:**\nThe companies state they are "left with no choice but to take all appropriate action to protect our legal rights" and will pursue business in the U.S. regardless.\n\n**Overall Stance:**\nThe press release frames the decision as a political sacrifice of American steelworkers\' futures and a betrayal of due process, with the companies vowing to fight the block legally.',
