    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided U.S. Steel Q4 2024 earnings presentation (dated January 30, 2025), here is a summary of the key points, with specific focus on the Nippon Steel merger:\n\n### Key Financial & Operational Highlights (Q4 2024 & Full Year 2024)\n\n- **Financial Performance:** Q4 2024 Adjusted EBITDA was **$190 million** (5% margin), down from Q3 2024 ($319 million) due to a challenging macro environment. Full Year 2024 Adjusted EBITDA was **$1.366 billion** (9% margin), down from $2.139 billion in 2023.\n- **Net Loss:** The company reported a net loss of **$89 million** ($0.39 per diluted share) in Q4 2024.\n- **Segment Performance:**\n    - **North American Flat-Rolled (NAFR):** Demonstrated resilience with a 10% EBITDA margin, benefiting from a strong commercial strategy and diverse product mix.\n    - **Mini Mill (Big River 2 / BR2):** Faced start-up costs (~$30M one-time) and ramp-related impacts (~$20M) in Q4, resulting in a negative 2% margin. However, the segment is expected to drive material EBITDA contribution in 2025.\n    - **U.S. Steel Europe (USSE):** Continued to struggle with a challenging demand environment, posting a negative 6% EBITDA margin.\n    - **Tubular:** Faced a challenging price environment despite an enhanced product offering.\n- **Liquidity:** Ended Q4 2024 with strong liquidity of **$3.6 billion**, including approximately $1.4 billion in cash.\n- **Strategic Projects (BR2):** The Big River 2 mini mill is ramping up. Construction is complete, and commissioning is underway. It is expected to reach run-rate throughput in the **second half of 2025** and full run-rate capability in **2026**.\n- **2025 Outlook:** Q1 2025 Adjusted EBITDA is forecast to be between **$100 million and $150 million**, reflecting seasonal headwinds and continued ramp-up costs at BR2 (~$50M).\n\n### Statements on the Nippon Steel (NSC) Merger & Business Impact\n\nThe presentation strongly reaffirms the company\'s commitment to the merger with Nippon Steel despite regulatory and legal challenges. Key statements include:\n\n- **Commitment to Close:** The company states it is "**committed to closing the transaction with Nippon Steel Corporation**" and is "**jointly taking legal action**" in response to alleged "wrongful interference."\n- **Transaction Value:** The companies are pursuing the deal to deliver **$55.00 per share** to U.S. Steel stockholders.\n- **Strategic Rationale (Impact on Operations):** The presentation frames the merger as the **"best path forward"** to secure the future of U.S. Steel. It claims the deal will:\n    - **Bring advanced technology and knowhow** ("world-leading integrated steelmaking") to the U.S.\n    - **Drive innovation and productivity**, enhancing U.S. Steel\'s global competitiveness.\n    - **Solidify the U.S. as a global leader** in steel production.\n- **Alignment with Policy:** The presentation asserts the transaction **"meets many of the goals set by President Trump regarding foreign direct investment and the need for foreign companies to manufacture in the United States."**\n\n**In summary, the presentation does not describe any impact of the deal on current operations. Instead, it emphasizes the merger as a future driver of operational excellence and growth, and highlights the ongoing legal strategy to overcome obstacles to the transaction.**',
